node.text: Commander Kelley Jones was raised to never give up. Her parents inspired her to take on new challenges, pursue her dreams and always give 100%. As a Surface Warfare Officer in the Navy, she never settled for less than her best. She led strike groups, traveled the world and became Captain of the first American crew to navigate the Faroe Islands. That’s how Kelley made her name mean Determination. #MakeYourName #NavyWomen

node.text: Your recruiter will be your guide through the enlistment process, which is a unique experience for every recruit. They will answer your questions, pull your paperwork together and prepare you for the next step. If you decide to join, your first steps will be to sign your paperwork and receive a medical examination. Then you’ll start processing, take a test, swear in and choose your Navy career. #ForgedByTheSea

node.text:
This #HispanicHeritageMonth, we wanted to honor all Hispanic Sailors and call out a few whose excellence has positively impacted our Naval history:

🌟 Admiral David Glasgow Farragut
Admiral Farragut led during the American Civil War and was the first person to say the iconic words, “Damn the torpedoes, full speed ahead!”

🌟 Admiral Horacio Rivero, Jr.
Admiral Rivero, Jr. was the first Puerto Rican and Hispanic four-star admiral, and he also became Vice Chief of Naval Operations in 1964.

🌟 Secretary of the Navy Edward Hidalgo
Eduardo Hidalgo was the first Secretary of the Navy of Hispanic descent. A first-generation American, with English as his second language, he is remembered for his selfless service.

🌟 Master Chief Joe R. Campa, Jr. 
Awarded with many meritorious military awards, Master Chief Campa, Jr. served as the 11th Master Chief Petty Officer of the Navy.

🌟 Rear Admiral Christina Alvarado
Awarded with many meritorious and commendation military awards, Rear Admiral Alvarado was the first nurse to command Naval Reserve Expeditionary Medical Facility Dallas One.

🌟 Rear Admiral Yvette Davids
The highly decorated Rear Admiral Davids was the first Hispanic female to command a warship in the U.S. Navy. Her most recent assignment was with the U.S. Department of State as the senior military advisor to the Assistant Secretary of State for Political-Military Affairs.

Thank you to all our Hispanic Sailors and their families for your service and commitment! #ForgedByTheSea

Memorizing the Sailor’s Creed BEFORE Boot Camp means one less worry when you arrive.

So, repeat after us:

“I am a United States Sailor.
I will support and defend the Constitution of the United States of America and I will obey the orders of those appointed over me.
I represent the fighting spirit of the Navy and those who have gone before me to defend freedom and democracy around the world.
I proudly serve my country's Navy combat team with Honor, Courage and Commitment.
I am committed to excellence and the fair treatment of all.”

Bravo Zulu! Stay tuned for our Sailor Lesson pop quiz to see how much of the Sailor’s Creed you remember. #ForgedByTheSea

node.text: From a young age, Desirae Martinez knew she could do anything she put her mind to.  When it came time to join the Navy as an Engineman, she had no trouble rolling up her sleeves. Meet one of the first female coxswains of the Mark VI Patrol Boat. #ForgedByTheSea
